      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "423bda883bb04cde",
      "text": "Listening Clock is a thought experiment about building a unique timepiece which recognises the time and date by interpreting the sounds we hear around us."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "feabd49b509d8ced",
      "text": "The clock contains algorithms which 'make sense' of time by the different types of noises which recur with differing periodicity. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bcd3331856ead823",
      "text": "Eventually noise rhythms which suggest diurnal cycling such as the silence at night, birds at first light etc, cause the algorithms to suggest a rough estimate of morning and night. As the amount of data processed increases, the guesstimate of midday or midnight becomes  better."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "98c9b8d4e5a8150b",
      "text": "Seasonal changes such as decreased outdoor activity in winter, energetic nature noises in spring, fans whirring in heat etc, enable the clock to start refining its guesstimation of the date in the year. Noisy celebrations such as New Year, or any regularly cycling events with fireworks also provide annual clues."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "556e40c7cd58ef85",
      "text": "Perhaps, listening clocks with the same algorithms would perform with different levels of accuracy according to where in the world they are listening. Remote audio listening would enable a clock to listen to a variety of  places around the world, separately or in combination."
    },
